# Design Principles

## 1. No Real Code for Authors

Authors should not write arbitrary code.

Instead of this:

```ts
if (gameState.flags["table.hasApple"]) {
  ...
}
```

Authors should configure this:

```md
Condition:
Flag table.hasApple is true
```

Instead of this:

```ts
gameState.inventory.push("apple")
```

Authors should configure this:

```md
Effect:
Add apple to inventory
```

## 2. Everything Is Data

Authored commands should be serializable in the world file.

A command should be saved as data like:

- IDs
- text strings
- lists
- conditions
- effects
- references to rooms/items/features/NPCs
- flags
- world variables
- timers

## 3. Prefer Structured Rules Over Scripting

Authors should build interactions from blocks:

- When...
- If...
- Then...
- Otherwise...
- After...
- Once...
- Repeat...

This keeps authored commands safe, debuggable, and editor-friendly.

## 4. World State Should Matter

The command language should heavily use state:

- Room visited/viewed flags
- Feature examined flags
- Inventory
- Item locations
- NPC locations
- NPC mood
- Object state
- Custom flags
- Counters
- Timers
- Turn count
- Previous player actions

## 5. Authored Commands Should Layer on Top of Generic Commands

The generic `put` command can say:

> You put the apple on the table.

But an authored rule can override or extend it:

> You set the apple on the table. A few minutes later, rats begin scratching in the walls.

The system should allow authored commands to:

- Replace the generic command
- Run before the generic command
- Run after the generic command
- Only run when conditions match
- Fall back to generic behavior when not matched

