# Final Recommendation

Build the system around **Interaction Rules**.

Each rule is:

```md
Trigger + Conditions + Effects
```

Use the existing command parser as the foundation, then add:

```md
Target resolution
Authored command definitions
Condition evaluator
Effect runner
Scheduled event processor
Expanded GameState
Editor UI for rules
```

The apple-on-table-rats scenario should be treated as the benchmark feature.

If the system can cleanly support that scenario, including cancellation, delayed consequences, room description changes, and NPC reactions, then the command language will be strong enough for most authored interactive fiction behavior.

The target design should let an author express:

```md
When the player puts food on the kitchen table,
if rats are not already present,
place the food on the table,
remember that food is there,
and after 3 turns,
if the food is still there,
bring rats into the kitchen.
```

Without writing code.

That is the heart of the system.